ry traces the ideas of a group of Western thinkers who sought to create, against a backdrop of anarchy, globally applicable economic rules. Their attempt, it turns out, succeeded all too well.” —Pankaj Mishra, Bloomberg Opinion “Fascinating, innovative…Slobodian has underlined the profound conservatism of the first generation of neoliberals and their fundamental hostility to democracy.” —Adam Tooze, Dissent “The definitive history of neoliberalism as a political project.” —Boston Review  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Aug 2021) 0aCapitalismxHistoryx20th century. 0aCapitalismxHistoryy20th century. 0aGlobalizationxHistoryx20th century. 0aGlobalizationxHistoryy20th century. 0aNeoliberalismxHistoryx20th century. 0aNeoliberalismxHistoryy20th century. 7aHISTORY / Modern / 20th Century.2bisacsh  aEuropean Economic Community.  aFriedrich Hayek.  aGATT.  aGeneral Agreement on Tariffs and Trade.  aGottfried Haberler.  aLeague of Nations.  aLionel Robbins.  aLudwig von Mises.  aMichael Heilperin.  aMont Pelerin Society.  aWTO.  aWilhelm Ropke.  aWorld Trade Organization.  aordoliberalism.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertHarvard University Press Complete eBook-Package 2018z978311060662140uhttps://doi.org/10.4159/978067491980840uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780674919808423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780674919808.jpg  a978-3-11-060662-1  Harvard University Press Complete eBook-Package 2018b2018  aGBV-deGruyter-alles